{"id":3003,"date":"2017-08-15T19:58:48","date_gmt":"2017-08-16T02:58:48","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/www.postgresqltutorial.com\/?page_id=3003"},"modified":"2020-07-09T23:20:08","modified_gmt":"2020-07-10T06:20:08","slug":"postgresql-localtime","status":"publish","type":"page","link":"https:\/\/www.postgresqltutorial.com\/postgresql-date-functions\/postgresql-localtime\/","title":{"rendered":"PostgreSQL LOCALTIME Function"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<p>The PostgreSQL <code>LOCALTIME<\/code> function returns the current time at which the current transaction starts.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Syntax<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The syntax of the <code>LOCALTIME<\/code> function is as follows:<\/p>\n\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><div><code class=\"hljs\">LOCALTIME(precision)<\/code><\/div><\/pre>\n\n\n<h2>Arguments<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The <code>LOCALTIME<\/code> function takes one optional argument:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>1) <code>precision<\/code><\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The <code>precision<\/code> argument specifies fractional seconds precision of the second field.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>If you omit the argument, it defaults to 6.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Return Value<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The <code>LOCALTIME<\/code> function returns a <code><a href=\"https:\/\/www.postgresqltutorial.com\/postgresql-time\/\">TIME<\/a><\/code> value that represents the time at which the current transaction starts.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Examples<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The following query illustrates how to get the time of the current transaction:<\/p>\n\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><div><code class=\"hljs\">SELECT LOCALTIME;<\/code><\/div><\/pre>\n\n\n<p>Here is the result:<\/p>\n\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\" aria-describedby=\"shcb-language-1\" data-shcb-language-name=\"CSS\" data-shcb-language-slug=\"css\"><div><code class=\"hljs language-css\">      <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\">time<\/span>\n<span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\">-----------------<\/span>\n 09<span class=\"hljs-selector-pseudo\">:52<\/span><span class=\"hljs-selector-pseudo\">:20.751278<\/span>\n(1 <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\">row<\/span>)<\/code><\/div><small class=\"shcb-language\" id=\"shcb-language-1\"><span class=\"shcb-language__label\">Code language:<\/span> <span class=\"shcb-language__name\">CSS<\/span> <span class=\"shcb-language__paren\">(<\/span><span class=\"shcb-language__slug\">css<\/span><span class=\"shcb-language__paren\">)<\/span><\/small><\/pre>\n\n\n<p>The get the time with a specified fractional seconds precision, you use the following statement:<\/p>\n\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><div><code class=\"hljs\">SELECT LOCALTIME(2);<\/code><\/div><\/pre>\n\n\n<p>The result is:<\/p>\n\n\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\" aria-describedby=\"shcb-language-2\" data-shcb-language-name=\"CSS\" data-shcb-language-slug=\"css\"><div><code class=\"hljs language-css\"><span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\">time<\/span>\n<span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\">-------------<\/span>\n 09<span class=\"hljs-selector-pseudo\">:53<\/span><span class=\"hljs-selector-pseudo\">:10.74<\/span>\n(1 <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\">row<\/span>)<\/code><\/div><small class=\"shcb-language\" id=\"shcb-language-2\"><span class=\"shcb-language__label\">Code language:<\/span> <span class=\"shcb-language__name\">CSS<\/span> <span class=\"shcb-language__paren\">(<\/span><span class=\"shcb-language__slug\">css<\/span><span class=\"shcb-language__paren\">)<\/span><\/small><\/pre>\n\n\n<h2>Remarks<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Noted that the <code>LOCATIME<\/code> function returns a <code>TIME<\/code> value without time zone while the <code><a href=\"https:\/\/www.postgresqltutorial.com\/postgresql-current_time\/\">CURRENT_TIME<\/a><\/code> function returns a <code>TIME<\/code> with time zone.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In this tutorial, you have learned how to use the PostgreSQL <code>LOCALTIME<\/code> function to get the time at which the current transaction starts.<\/p>\n<div class=\"helpful-block-content\" data-title=\"\">\n\t<header>\n\t\t<div class=\"wth-question\">Was this